{"accepted":[{"assertion":"Formal-Conjectures statement: Erdos119.erdos_119.parts.ii https://google-deepmind.github.io/formal-conjectures/theorem/?name=Erdos119.erdos_119.parts.ii.","id":"vf_4f921191714e9936","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Erdős Problem #119: declared status 'open'. Formalized: yes. Let $z_i$ be an infinite sequence of complex numbers such that $\\lvert z_i\\rvert=1$ for all $i\\geq 1$, and for $n\\geq 1$ let\\[p_n(z)=\\prod_{i\\leq n} (z-z_i).\\]Let $M_n=\\max_{\\lvert z\\rvert=1}\\lvert p_n(z)\\rvert$.\n\nIs it true that $\\limsup M_n=\\infty$?\n\nIs it true that there exists $c>0$ such that for infinitely many $n$ we have $M_n > n^c$?\n\nIs it true that there exists $c>0$ such that, for all large $n$,\\[\\sum_{k\\leq n}M_k > n^{1+c}?\\] Current best: The second question was answered by Beck \\cite{Be91}, who proved that there exists some $c>0$ such that\\[\\max_{n\\leq N} M_n > N^c.\\]Erd\\H{o}s (e.g. see \\cite{Ha74}) gave a construction of a sequence with $M_n\\leq n+1$ for all $n$. Linden \\cite{Li77} improved this to give a sequence with $M_n\\ll n^{1-c}$ for some $c>0$. Prize: $100. Tags: analysis, polynomials.","id":"vf_f5e763f0c18fabb9","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"}],"accepted_activity":false,"activity":[],"activity_types":[],"attempt_count":0,"banked_attempt_count":0,"commits":[],"dependency_impact":"none","detail_url":"problems/119.json","draft_proposals":[],"edges":[{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"vf_4f921191714e9936","source_root":"sha256:d3db36661e28b7570fc8704bf8455b80d8382beded47d069f2c386144d90a238","target":"erdos:119","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Materialized typed link between accepted findings.","inferred":true,"relation":"synthesized_from","source":"vf_4f921191714e9936","source_root":"sha256:d3db36661e28b7570fc8704bf8455b80d8382beded47d069f2c386144d90a238","target":"vf_f5e763f0c18fabb9","tr